  "summary": "Jimmy and Ronnie DeFleur drive to Dean's Priory after Ronnie hesitates to share information regarding Gary Wade. During the drive, Ronnie asks about Gerry’s sister, and Jimmy describes her as remarkable. Upon arriving at the Priory, they meet Miss Wade, a petite girl with blue eyes and two black, long-eared dogs. Jimmy introduces Ronnie, and Ronnie informs Miss Wade that Grimm is dead. Although she initially questions if Gerry died from sleeping pills, she eventually asks for details regarding the death. Miss Wade expresses a desire to be alone and states she will arrive at Chimney House later in her two-seater sports car.\n\nReturning to Chimney House, Jimmy encounters a tearful Mrs. Cutt. Ronnie, having just left Greta Wade's room, insists that Jimmy enter the room to pay his respects to the deceased. Inside, Jimmy observes Gerry Wade's pale, motionless body on a bed covered in white flowers. He notices a row of clocks on the mantelpiece and discovers that there are only seven clocks instead of eight, prompting him to wonder why one is missing.\n\nIn a separate scene, Lord Kettlemere discusses the nature of successful, self-centered people with his daughter, Miss Elinor Brent (known as \"Bondel\"). They discuss land reclaimed from Old Quart. Lord Kettlemere expresses his distaste for oppressive, strong-willed individuals and mentions his opposition to autopsies, noting that a similar trouble occurred four years ago due to George Lomax.",
